-- ⚠️ RE-PINNED 2026-07-14 — THE S2 INVERSION.  `eq 1 2` now prints 3, was False.
-- THIS FIXTURE IS THE HEADLINE BUG IN MINIATURE.  P0-20 (below) made check/run/build
-- AGREE — but it made them agree on DISPATCHING to `impl Eq Int`, which silently
-- ERASED the user`s `eq : Int -> Int -> Int`.  Agreement was never the whole story:
-- by S7 all three paths agree on every shadow cell, which is exactly why no
-- differential gate could ever see this bug.  A top-level name is now the module`s
-- own name: `eq 1 2` calls the user`s `eq` and prints 3.
-- The P0-20 history below is still accurate about the bug it fixed; only the
-- tie-break it restored (dispatch) has been inverted.
--
-- P0-20 (SILENT WRONG ANSWER — the worst cell yet found in the shadow arc).
--
-- A top-level `eq` shadowing the PRELUDE's `Eq` method `eq`, applied to LITERAL
-- receivers.  Before the fix the three engines each did something different:
--
--   check  typed `eq 1 2` as Int (the standalone)         -> 0 diagnostics
--   run    DISPATCHED to `impl Eq Int`, got a Bool        -> E-PANIC "intToString"
--   build  DISPATCHED too, and printed it as an Int       -> SILENTLY PRINTED 0
--
-- Root cause: a numeric literal is `Num a => a`, i.e. UNGROUNDED at inference time, so
-- typecheck took the ungrounded arm (S5 => standalone) — but typing the site against the
-- standalone's scheme UNIFIES `Int` into the receiver, so the POST-inference route
-- resolver saw a grounded `Int`, found `impl Eq Int`, and dispatched.  The type came from
-- one arm and the route from the other.  See groundShadowReceiver in typecheck.mdk.
--
-- SHADOW-SEMANTICS S2 is unambiguous about the answer: the receiver grounds to `Int` and
-- `Eq Int` has an impl, so this DISPATCHES.  `println (eq 1 2)` prints False on all three
-- engines; the user's own `eq` is reachable only at a type with no `Eq` impl.
eq : Int -> Int -> Int
eq a b = a + b

main = println (eq 1 2)
